on-id">An example of what the common (yet confusing) expression "steep lear=
ning curve" is referring to. The subject spends a great amount of time but =
does not see an increase in proficiency at first.</span> View <a href=3D"ht=
tps://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/Data:Example_of_a_steep_learning_curve.tab=
" class=3D"extiw" title=3D"c:Data:Example of a steep learning curve.tab">so=
urce data</a>.</div></div></div>=20
<p>A <b>learning curve</b> is a graphical representation of the relationshi=
p between how <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Skill" title=3D"Skil=
l">proficient</a> people are at a task and the amount of <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Experience" title=3D"Experience">experience</a> they=
 have. Proficiency (measured on the vertical axis) usually increases with i=
ncreased experience (the horizontal axis), that is to say, the more someone=
, groups, companies or industries perform a task, the better their performa=
nce at the task.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-businessdictionary._com_1-0" class=3D"r=
eference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Learning_curve#cite_note=
-businessdictionary._com-1"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>1<span cla=
ss=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The common expression "a steep learning curve" is a <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Misnomer" title=3D"Misnomer">misnomer</a> suggesti=
ng that an activity is difficult to learn and that expending much effort do=
es not increase proficiency by much, although a <a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Learning" title=3D"Learning">learning</a> curve with a steep =
start actually represents rapid progress.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-surg_2-0" clas=
s=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Learning_curve#cit=
e_note-surg-2"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>2<span class=3D"cite-br=
acket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-zimmer_3-0" class=3D"reference=
"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Learning_curve#cite_note-zimmer-=
3"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>3<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</sp=
an></a></sup> In fact, the gradient of the curve has nothing to do with the=
 overall difficulty of an activity, but expresses the expected rate of chan=
ge of learning speed over time. An activity that it is easy to learn the ba=
sics of, but difficult to gain proficiency in, may be described as having "=
a steep learning curve".<sup class=3D"noprint Inline-Template Template-Fact=
" style=3D"white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Wikipedia:Citation_needed" title=3D"Wikipedia:Citation needed"><span titl=
e=3D"This claim needs references to reliable sources. (July 2023)">citation=
 needed</span></a></i>]</sup>
</p><p>The learning curve may refer to a specific task or a <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Body_of_knowledge" title=3D"Body of knowledge">bo=
dy of knowledge</a>. <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hermann_Ebbin=
ghaus" title=3D"Hermann Ebbinghaus">Hermann Ebbinghaus</a> first described =
the learning curve in 1885 in the field of the psychology of learning, alth=
ough the name did not come into use until 1903.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-ebbing_b=
ook_4-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Learn=
ing_curve#cite_note-ebbing_book-4"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>4<s=
pan class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-books.goog=
le.com_5-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Le=
arning_curve#cite_note-books.google.com-5"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</=
span>5<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> In 1936 <a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Theodore_Paul_Wright" title=3D"Theodore Paul Wr=
ight">Theodore Paul Wright</a> described the effect of learning on <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Production_costs" class=3D"mw-redirect" t=
itle=3D"Production costs">production costs</a> in the <a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Aircraft_industry" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Aircr=
aft industry">aircraft industry</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Wright,_T.P._1936_6=
-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Learning_c=
urve#cite_note-Wright,_T.P._1936-6"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>6<=
span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> This form, in which <i>unit =
cost</i> is plotted against <i>total production</i>, is sometimes called an=
 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Experience_curve" class=3D"mw-red=
irect" title=3D"Experience curve">experience curve</a>, or <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wright%27s_Law" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Wri=
ght's Law">Wright's law</a>.
</p>
