<p>Several main functions have been used:<sup id=3D"cite_ref-23" class=3D"r=
eference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Learning_curve#cite_note=
-23"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>23<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]<=
/span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-24" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Learning_curve#cite_note-24"><span class=3D"cite-=
bracket">[</span>24<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-25" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Learning_curve#cite_note-25"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>25<spa=
n class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<ul><li>The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sigmoid_function" titl=
e=3D"Sigmoid function">S-Curve or Sigmoid function</a> is the idealized gen=
eral form of all learning curves, with slowly accumulating small steps at f=
irst followed by larger steps and then successively smaller ones later, as =
the learning activity reaches its limit. That idealizes the normal progress=
ion from discovery of something to learn about followed to the limit of lea=
rning about it. The other shapes of learning curves (4, 5 &amp; 6) show seg=
ments of S-curves without their full extents. In this case the improvement =
of proficiency starts slowly, then increases rapidly, and finally levels of=
f.</li>
<li>Exponential growth; the proficiency can increase without limit, as in <=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Exponential_growth" title=3D"Expone=
ntial growth">Exponential growth</a></li>
<li>Exponential rise or fall to a Limit; proficiency can exponentially appr=
oach a limit in a manner similar to that in which a capacitor charges or di=
scharges (<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Exponential_decay" title=
=3D"Exponential decay">exponential decay</a>) through a resistor. The incre=
ase in skill or retention of information may increase rapidly to its maximu=
m rate during the initial attempts, and then gradually levels out, meaning =
that the subject's skill does not improve much with each later repetition, =
with less new knowledge gained over time.</li>
<li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Power_law" title=3D"Power law"=
>Power law</a>; similar in appearance to an <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Exponential_decay" title=3D"Exponential decay">exponential decay<=
/a> function, and is almost always used for a decreasing performance metric=
, such as cost. It also has the property that if plotted as the <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Logarithm" title=3D"Logarithm">logarithm</a> =
of proficiency against the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Logarit=
hm" title=3D"Logarithm">logarithm</a> of experience the result is a straigh=
t line, and it is often presented that way.</li></ul>
<p>The specific case of a plot of Unit Cost versus Total Production with a =
power law was named the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Experience=
_curve" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Experience curve">experience curve</=
a>: the mathematical function is sometimes called Henderson's Law. This for=
m of learning curve is used extensively in industry for cost projections.<s=
up id=3D"cite_ref-26" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Learning_curve#cite_note-26"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>2=
6<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"In_machine_learning">In mac=
hine learning</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsect=
ion-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=
=3DLearning_curve&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D7" title=3D"Edit section:=
 In machine learning"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-br=
acket">]</span></span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Further information: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Learning_curv=
e_(machine_learning)" title=3D"Learning curve (machine learning)">Learning =
curve (machine learning)</a></div>
<p>Plots relating performance to experience are widely used in <a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Machine_learning" title=3D"Machine learning">m=
achine learning</a>. Performance is the error rate or accuracy of the <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Learning" title=3D"Learning">learning</=
a> system, while experience may be the number of training examples used for=
 learning or the number of iterations used in <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Optimizing" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Optimizing">optimizi=
ng</a> the system model parameters.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-27" class=3D"referen=
ce"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Learning_curve#cite_note-27"><=
span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>27<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span>=
</a></sup> The machine learning curve is useful for many purposes including=
 comparing different algorithms,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-28" class=3D"reference"=
><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Learning_curve#cite_note-28"><spa=
n class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>28<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a=
></sup>  choosing model parameters during design,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-29" cl=
ass=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Learning_curve#c=
ite_note-29"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>29<span class=3D"cite-bra=
cket">]</span></a></sup> adjusting optimization to improve convergence, and=
 determining the amount of data used for training.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-30" c=
lass=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Learning_curve#=
cite_note-30"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>30<span class=3D"cite-br=
acket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Broader_interpretations">Br=
oader interpretations</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-=
editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.ph=
p?title=3DLearning_curve&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D8" title=3D"Edit s=
ection: Broader interpretations"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-edi=
tsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>Initially introduced in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Educati=
onal_psychology" title=3D"Educational psychology">educational</a> and <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Behavioral_psychology" class=3D"mw-redi=
rect" title=3D"Behavioral psychology">behavioral psychology</a>, the term h=
as acquired a broader interpretation over time, and expressions such as "ex=
perience curve", "improvement curve", "cost improvement curve", "progress c=
urve", "progress function", "startup curve", and "efficiency curve" are oft=
en used interchangeably. In economics the subject is rates of "<a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Economic_development" title=3D"Economic develo=
pment">development</a>", as development refers to a whole system learning p=
rocess with varying rates of progression. Generally speaking all learning d=
isplays <b>incremental change</b> over time, but describes an <b><a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sigmoid_function" title=3D"Sigmoid function"=
>"S" curve</a></b> which has different appearances depending on the time sc=
ale of observation. It has now also become associated with the evolutionary=
 theory of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Punctuated_equilibrium"=
 title=3D"Punctuated equilibrium">punctuated equilibrium</a> and other kind=
s of <b>revolutionary change</b> in complex systems generally, relating to =
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Innovation" title=3D"Innovation">i=
nnovation</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Organizational_beha=
vior" title=3D"Organizational behavior">organizational behavior</a> and the=
 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Management" title=3D"Management">=
management</a> of group learning, among other fields.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-31=
" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Learning_cur=
ve#cite_note-31"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>31<span class=3D"cite=
-bracket">]</span></a></sup> These processes of rapidly emerging new form a=
ppear to take place by complex learning within the systems themselves, whic=
h when observable, display curves of changing rates that accelerate and dec=
elerate.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"General_learning_limits">Ge=
neral learning limits</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-=
editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.ph=
p?title=3DLearning_curve&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D9" title=3D"Edit s=
ection: General learning limits"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-edi=
tsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p><i>Learning curves</i>, also called <i>experience curves</i>, relate to =
the much broader subject of natural limits for resources and technologies i=
n general. Such limits generally present themselves as increasing complicat=
ions that slow the learning of how to do things more efficiently, like the =
well-known limits of perfecting any process or product or to perfecting mea=
surements.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-32" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Learning_curve#cite_note-32"><span class=3D"cite-bracke=
t">[</span>32<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> These practica=
l experiences match the predictions of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Second_law_of_thermodynamics" title=3D"Second law of thermodynamic=
s">second law of thermodynamics</a> for the limits of waste reduction gener=
ally. Approaching limits of perfecting things to eliminate waste meets geom=
etrically increasing effort to make progress, and provides an environmental=
 measure of all factors seen and unseen changing the learning experience. P=
erfecting things becomes ever more difficult despite increasing effort desp=
ite continuing positive, if ever diminishing, results. The same kind of slo=
wing progress due to complications in learning also appears in the limits o=
f useful technologies and of profitable markets applying to <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Product_life_cycle_management" class=3D"mw-redire=
ct" title=3D"Product life cycle management">product life cycle management</=
a> and <a rel=3D"nofollow" class=3D"external text" href=3D"http://www.actap=
ress.com/PaperInfo.aspx?PaperID=3D19159&amp;reason=3D500">software developm=
ent cycles</a>). Remaining market segments or remaining potential efficienc=
ies or efficiencies are found in successively less convenient forms.
</p><p>Efficiency and development curves typically follow a two-phase proce=
ss of first bigger steps corresponding to finding things easier, followed b=
y smaller steps of finding things more difficult. It reflects bursts of lea=
rning following breakthroughs that make learning easier followed by meeting=
 constraints that make learning ever harder, perhaps toward a point of cess=
ation.
</p>
<ul><li><b>Natural Limits</b> One of the key studies in the area concerns d=
iminishing returns on investments generally, either physical or financial, =
pointing to whole system limits for resource development or other efforts. =
The most studied of these may be <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/E=
nergy_Return_on_Energy_Invested" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Energy Retu=
rn on Energy Invested">Energy Return on Energy Invested</a> or EROEI, discu=
ssed at length in an <a rel=3D"nofollow" class=3D"external text" href=3D"ht=
tp://www.eoearth.org/article/Energy_return_on_investment_(EROI)">Encycloped=
ia of the Earth article</a> and in an <a rel=3D"nofollow" class=3D"external=
 text" href=3D"http://www.theoildrum.com/node/3412">OilDrum article</a> and=
 <a rel=3D"nofollow" class=3D"external text" href=3D"http://www.theoildrum.=
com/node/3786">series</a> also referred to as <a rel=3D"nofollow" class=3D"=
external text" href=3D"http://www.dani2989.com/matiere1/hubbertpeakoilgb.ht=
m">Hubert curves</a>. The energy needed to produce energy is a measure of o=
ur difficulty in learning how to make remaining energy resources useful in =
relation to the effort expended. Energy returns on energy invested have bee=
n in continual decline for some time, caused by natural resource limits and=
 increasing investment. Energy is both nature's and our own principal resou=
rce for making things happen. The point of diminishing returns is when incr=
easing investment makes the resource more expensive. As natural limits are =
approached, easily used sources are exhausted and ones with more complicati=
ons need to be used instead. As an environmental signal persistently dimini=
shing EROI indicates an approach of whole system limits in our <a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Learning_power" title=3D"Learning power">abili=
ty</a> to make things happen.</li>
<li><b>Useful Natural Limits</b> EROEI measures the return on invested effo=
rt as a ratio of R/I or <i>learning progress</i>. The inverse I/R measures =
<i>learning difficulty</i>. The simple difference is that if R approaches z=
ero R/I will too, but I/R will approach infinity. When complications emerge=
 to limit learning progress the limit of <i>useful returns</i>, uR, is appr=
oached and R-uR approaches zero. The <i>difficulty of useful learning</i> I=
/(R-uR) approaches infinity as increasingly difficult tasks make the effort=
 unproductive. That point is approached as a vertical asymptote, at a parti=
cular point in time, that can be delayed only by unsustainable effort. It d=
efines a point at which enough investment has been made and the <i>task is =
done</i>, usually planned to be the same as when the <i>task is complete</i=
>. For unplanned tasks it may be either foreseen or discovered by surprise.=
 The usefulness measure, uR, is affected by the complexity of environmental=
 responses that can only be measured when they occur unless they are forese=
en.</li></ul>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"In_culture">In culture</h2>=
<span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</sp=
an><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DLearning_curve&a=
mp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D10" title=3D"Edit section: In culture"><span=
>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div=
>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"&quot;Steep_learning_curve&=
quot;"><span id=3D".22Steep_learning_curve.22"></span>"Steep learning curve=
"</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket"=
>[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DLearning_c=
urve&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D11" title=3D"Edit section: &quot;Steep=
 learning curve&quot;"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-b=
racket">]</span></span></div>
<p>The expression "steep learning curve" is used with opposite meanings. Mo=
st sources, including the <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Oxfor=
d_Dictionary_of_English" title=3D"Oxford Dictionary of English">Oxford Dict=
ionary of English</a></i>, the <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
American_Heritage_Dictionary_of_the_English_Language" class=3D"mw-redirect"=
 title=3D"American Heritage Dictionary of the English Language">American He=
ritage Dictionary of the English Language</a></i>, and <i><a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Merriam-Webster%27s_Collegiate_Dictionary" class=3D=
"mw-redirect" title=3D"Merriam-Webster's Collegiate Dictionary">Merriam-Web=
ster's Collegiate Dictionary</a></i>, define a learning curve as the rate a=
t which skill is acquired, so a steep increase would mean a quick increment=
 of skill.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-surg_2-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Learning_curve#cite_note-surg-2"><span class=3D"c=
ite-bracket">[</span>2<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup i=
d=3D"cite_ref-grammarphobia_33-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Learning_curve#cite_note-grammarphobia-33"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>33<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
However, the term is often used in common English with the meaning of a dif=
ficult initial learning process.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-zimmer_3-3" class=3D"re=
ference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Learning_curve#cite_note-=
zimmer-3"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>3<span class=3D"cite-bracket=
">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-grammarphobia_33-1" class=3D"refere=
nce"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Learning_curve#cite_note-gram=
marphobia-33"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>33<span class=3D"cite-br=
acket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The common English usage aligns with a metaphorical interpretation o=
f the learning curve as a hill to climb. (A steeper hill is initially hard,=
 while a gentle slope is less strainful, though sometimes rather tedious. A=
ccordingly, the shape of the curve (hill) may not indicate the total amount=
 of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Work_(physics)" title=3D"Work =
(physics)">work</a> required. Instead, it can be understood as a matter of =
preference related to ambition, personality and learning style.)
</p>
