<p>The term <i>learning curve</i> with meanings of <i>easy</i> and <i>diffi=
cult</i> can be described with adjectives like <i>short</i> and <i>long</i>=
 rather than <i>shallow</i> and <i>steep</i>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-surg_2-2" =
class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Learning_curve=
#cite_note-surg-2"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>2<span class=3D"cit=
e-bracket">]</span></a></sup> If two products have similar functionality th=
en the one with a "steep" curve is probably better, because it can be learn=
ed in a shorter time. On the other hand, if two products have different fun=
ctionality, then one with a <i>short</i> curve (a short time to learn) and =
limited functionality may not be as good as one with a <i>long</i> curve (a=
 long time to learn) and greater functionality.
</p><p>For example, the Windows program <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Notepad_(Windows)" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Notepad (Windows)">=
Notepad</a> is extremely simple to learn, but offers little after this. At =
the other extreme is the UNIX terminal editor <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Vim_(text_editor)" title=3D"Vim (text editor)">vi or Vim</a>, w=
hich is difficult to learn, but offers a wide array of features after the u=
ser has learned how to use it.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"&quot;On_a_steep_learning_c=
urve&quot;"><span id=3D".22On_a_steep_learning_curve.22"></span>"On a steep=
 learning curve"</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-edits=
ection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?tit=
le=3DLearning_curve&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D12" title=3D"Edit secti=
on: &quot;On a steep learning curve&quot;"><span>edit</span></a><span class=
=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ben_Zimmer" title=3D"Ben Zimmer=
">Ben Zimmer</a> discusses the use of the term "on a steep learning curve" =
in <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Downton_Abbey" title=3D"Down=
ton Abbey">Downton Abbey</a></i>, a television series set in the early 20th=
 century, concentrating mainly on whether use of the term is an <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Anachronism" title=3D"Anachronism">anachronis=
m</a>. "Matthew Crawley, the presumptive heir of Downton Abbey and now the =
co-owner of the estate, says, 'I've been on a steep learning curve since ar=
riving at Downton.' By this he means that he has had a difficult time learn=
ing the ways of Downton, but people did not start talking that way until th=
e 1970s."<sup id=3D"cite_ref-zimmer_3-4" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Learning_curve#cite_note-zimmer-3"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>3<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><=
sup id=3D"cite_ref-34" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Learning_curve#cite_note-34"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>=
34<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Zimmer also comments that the popular use of <i>steep</i> as <i>diff=
icult</i> is a reversal of the technical meaning. He identifies the first u=
se of <i>steep learning curve</i> as 1973, and the <i>arduous</i> interpret=
ation as 1978.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Difficulty_curves_in_video_=
games">Difficulty curves in video games</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection">=
<span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/w/index.php?title=3DLearning_curve&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D=
13" title=3D"Edit section: Difficulty curves in video games"><span>edit</sp=
an></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p><span class=3D"anchor" id=3D"Difficulty_curve"></span>
The idea of learning curves is often translated into <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Video_game" title=3D"Video game">video game</a> gameplay=
 as a "difficulty curve", which described how hard the game may get as the =
player progresses through the game and requiring the player to either becom=
e more proficient with the game, gain better understanding of the game's me=
chanics, and/or spend time "<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Grindi=
ng_(video_games)" title=3D"Grinding (video games)">grinding</a>" to improve=
 their characters. Establishing the right difficulty curve is part of achie=
ving the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Game_balance" title=3D"Ga=
me balance">game balance</a> within a title. As with learning curves in edu=
cational settings, difficulty curves can have multitudes of shapes, and gam=
es may frequently provide various levels of difficulty that change the shap=
e of this curve relative to its default to make the game harder or easier.<=
sup id=3D"cite_ref-35" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Learning_curve#cite_note-35"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>=
35<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-36" cl=
ass=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Learning_curve#c=
ite_note-36"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>36<span class=3D"cite-bra=
cket">]</span></a></sup> Optimally the difficulty of a <a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Video_game" title=3D"Video game">video game</a> increa=
ses in correspondence with players ability. Games must neither be too chall=
enging nor too undemanding nor too fortuitous.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-RuggillMc=
Allister2011_37-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Learning_curve#cite_note-RuggillMcAllister2011-37"><span class=3D"cite=
-bracket">[</span>37<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The pla=
yers will continue playing as long as a game is perceived to be winnable. T=
his is therefore referred to as the <i>illusion of winnability</i>. To gene=
rate an illusion of winnability games can include, internal value (a sense =
of moving towards a goal and being rewarded for it) driven by conflict whic=
h can be generated by an antagonistic environment and story driven suspense=
 in the form of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/World_building" cl=
ass=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"World building">world building</a>. The latter=
 is not pivotal to progressing in a game.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Wolf2020_38-0"=
 class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Learning_curv=
e#cite_note-Wolf2020-38"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>38<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Game designers may also make changes i=
n <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gameplay" title=3D"Gameplay">gam=
eplay</a> by, for instance, limiting resources. One perspective is that if =
players are not tricked to believe that the video game world is real - if t=
he world does not feel vibrant - then there is no point in creating the gam=
e.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Richard2010_39-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Learning_curve#cite_note-Richard2010-39"><span cl=
ass=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>39<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></s=
up><sup id=3D"cite_ref-Holmes2012_40-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Learning_curve#cite_note-Holmes2012-40"><span cla=
ss=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>40<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></su=
p>
</p>
